The '''''Zumwalt''-class destroyer''' is a class of three [[United States Navy]] [[guided-missile destroyer]]s designed as multi-mission [[stealth ship]]s with a focus on land attack. The class was designed with a primary role of [[naval gunfire support]] and secondary roles of surface warfare and [[anti-aircraft warfare]]. The class design emerged from the [[DD-21]] "land attack destroyer" program as "DD(X)" and was intended to take the role of [[battleship]]s in meeting a congressional mandate for naval fire support.<ref>Section 1011 of the National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 1996 (Public Law 104-106; 110 Stat. 421)</ref> The ship was designed around its two [[Advanced Gun System]]s (AGS), utilizing unique [[Long Range Land Attack Projectile]] (LRLAP) ammunition.<ref name=LaGrone>{{cite web|url= https://news.usni.org/2018/01/11/no-new-round-planned-zumwalt-destroyer-gun-system-navy-monitoring-industry|title= No New Round Planned For Zumwalt Destroyer Gun System; Navy Monitoring Industry|last= LaGrone|first= Sam|date= 11 January 2018|website= USNI News|publisher= U.S. Naval Institute|access-date= 2018-03-02|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180303050317/https://news.usni.org/2018/01/11/no-new-round-planned-zumwalt-destroyer-gun-system-navy-monitoring-industry|archive-date= 3 March 2018|url-status= live}}</ref> LRLAP procurement was canceled, rendering the guns unusable,<ref name=LaGrone/> so the Navy re-purposed the ships for surface warfare.<ref name=Eckstein>{{cite web|url= https://news.usni.org/2017/12/04/navy-refocus-ddg-1000-surface-strike|title= New Requirements for DDG-1000 Focus on Surface Strike|last= Eckstein|first= Megan|date= 4 December 2017|website= USNI News|publisher= U.S. Naval Institute|access-date= 2018-03-02|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180304054809/https://news.usni.org/2017/12/04/navy-refocus-ddg-1000-surface-strike|archive-date= 4 March 2018|url-status= live}}</ref> In 2023, the Navy began removing the AGS from the ships and replaced them with [[hypersonic missile]]s.<ref name="remove">{{cite web|last=LaGrone|first=Sam|title=Latest Zumwalt Hypersonic Missile Installation Plan Calls For Removing Gun Mounts|date=March 16, 2022|access-date= May 8, 2022|url=https://news.usni.org/2022/03/16/latest-zumwalt-hypersonic-missile-installation-plan-calls-for-removing-gun-mounts|work= USNI News}}</ref>

The ships are classed as destroyers, but they are now the largest surface combatants in the US Navy,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lundquist |first1=Edward |title=Ship Conversion: USS Zumwalt Modified for Hypersonic Missiles |url=https://www.marinelink.com/news/ship-conversion-uss-zumwalt-modified-521318 |work=MarineLink |date=20 January 2025 |language=en}}</ref> much larger than any other active [[destroyer]]s or [[cruiser]]s.<ref name="Marinelink">{{Cite web |author=Lundquist, Edward |title=The Navy's Battlewagon of the 21st Century |url=https://magazines.marinelink.com/Magazines/MaritimeReporter/201312/content/navys-battlewagon-century-211855 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405211159/https://magazines.marinelink.com/Magazines/MaritimeReporter/201312/content/navys-battlewagon-century-211855 |archive-date=5 April 2019 |access-date=5 April 2019 |website=Marinelink.com}}</ref> The vessels' distinctive appearance results from the design requirement for a low [[radar cross-section]] (RCS). The ''Zumwalt'' class has a [[wave-piercing]] [[tumblehome]] hull form whose sides slope inward above the waterline, dramatically reducing RCS by returning much less energy than a conventional flare hull form.

The class has an [[integrated electric propulsion]] (IEP) system that can send electricity from its turbo-generators to the electric drive motors or weapons, the [[Total Ship Computing Environment Infrastructure]] (TSCEI), automated fire-fighting systems, and automated piping rupture isolation.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Sanchez |first=Lucia |title=Electromagnetic Railgun – A "Navy After Next" Game Changer |url=https://www.doncio.navy.mil/chips/ArticleDetails.aspx?ID=2984 |journal=CHIPS – the Department of the Navy Information Technology Magazine |date=January–March 2007 |access-date=13 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111060230/http://www.doncio.navy.mil/chips/ArticleDetails.aspx?ID=2984 |archive-date=11 November 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> The class is designed to require a smaller crew and to be less expensive to operate than comparable warships.

The lead ship is named {{USS|Zumwalt|DDG-1000|2}} for Admiral [[Elmo Zumwalt]] and carries the hull number DDG-1000. Originally, 32 ships were planned, with $9.6&nbsp;billion research and development costs spread across the class. As costs overran estimates, the number was reduced to 24, then to 7; finally, in July 2008, the Navy requested that Congress stop procuring ''Zumwalt''s and revert to building more ''[[Arleigh Burke-class destroyer|Arleigh Burke]]'' destroyers.  Only three ''Zumwalt''s were ultimately built.  The average costs of construction accordingly increased, to $4.24&nbsp;billion,<ref name=GAO-15-342SP /><ref name="ndaa69-70" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Cutting-edge Navy warship being built in Maine |url=http://www.foxnews.com/scitech/2012/04/12/cutting-edge-navy-warship-being-built-in-maine/?test=latestnews |publisher=Fox News |date=12 April 2012 |access-date=12 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415052649/http://www.foxnews.com/scitech/2012/04/12/cutting-edge-navy-warship-being-built-in-maine/?test=latestnews |archive-date=15 April 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=cost_april2016/> well exceeding the per-unit cost of a nuclear-powered {{sclass|Virginia|submarine}} ($2.688&nbsp;billion),<ref>The US Navy's budget request for two Virginias in fiscal year 2016 (FY2016) was $5,376.9&nbsp;million, including $2,030.4M for advance funding from previous years.</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/weapons/RL32418.pdf |title= RL32418, Navy Virginia (SSN-774) Class Attack Submarine Procurement: Background and Issues for Congress |work=Congressional Research Service |date= 27 May 2016 |access-date=17 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006194640/https://www.fas.org/sgp/crs/weapons/RL32418.pdf |archive-date=6 October 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> and with the program's large development costs now attributable to only three ships, rather than the 32 originally planned, the total program cost per ship jumped.  In April 2016 the total program cost was $22.5&nbsp;billion,<ref name=cost_april2016/> $7.5&nbsp;billion per ship.  The per-ship increases triggered a [[Nunn–McCurdy Amendment]] breach.<ref>"Root Cause Analyses of Nunn-McCurdy Breaches – Zumwalt-Class Destroyer, Joint Strike Fighter, Longbow Apache, and Wideband Global Satellite," Rand Corporation (2011); see Vol. 1, Ch. 3 via http://www.rand.org/pubs/monographs/MG1171z1.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019175210/http://www.rand.org/pubs/monographs/MG1171z1.html |date=19 October 2016}}</ref>

==History==

===Background and funding===
Many of the features were developed under the [[DD-21]] program ("21st Century Destroyer"), which was originally designed around the [[Advanced Gun System|Vertical Gun for Advanced Ships]] (VGAS). In 2001, Congress cut the DD-21 program by half as part of the [[SC21 (United States)|SC21]] program; to save it, the acquisition program was renamed DD(X) and heavily reworked.

Originally, the Navy had hoped to build 32 destroyers. That number was reduced to 24, then to 7, due to the high cost of new and experimental technologies.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Francis |first1=Paul L. |title=Cost to Deliver Zumwalt-Class Destroyers Likely to Exceed Budget |url=https://www.gao.gov/assets/gao-08-804.pdf |publisher=United States Government Accountability Office |access-date=2 October 2022 |page=54 |date=July 2008}}</ref> On 23 November 2005, the Defense Acquisition Board approved a plan for simultaneous construction of the first two ships at [[Northrop Grumman]]'s [[Ingalls Shipbuilding|Ingalls yard]] in [[Pascagoula, Mississippi]], and [[General Dynamics]]' [[Bath Iron Works]] in [[Bath, Maine]]. However, at that date, funding had yet to be authorized by Congress.

In late December 2005, the House and Senate agreed to continue funding the program. The [[United States House of Representatives|US House of Representatives]] allotted the Navy only enough money to begin construction on one destroyer as a "technology demonstrator". The initial funding allocation was included in the National Defense Authorization Act of 2007.<ref name="ndaa69-70">{{cite book |title=109th Congress :Department of Defense Appropriations Act, 2007 |url=http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=109_cong_public_laws&docid=f:publ289.109 |date=29 September 2006 |publisher=(109–289) US Government Printing Office |access-date=11 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090216022149/http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=109_cong_public_laws&docid=f:publ289.109 |archive-date=16 February 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref> However, this was increased to two ships by the 2007 appropriations bill<ref name="AP060926">{{cite news |last=Taylor |first=Andrew |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/09/26/AR2006092601011_2.html |title=House OKs $70B for Iraq, Afghanistan |agency=Associated Press |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=26 September 2006 |access-date=19 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709170839/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/09/26/AR2006092601011_2.html |archive-date=9 July 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> approved in September 2006, which allotted US$2.568&nbsp;billion to the DDG-1000 program.<ref name="ndaa69-70" />

On 31 July 2008, US Navy acquisition officials told Congress that the service needed to purchase more {{sclass|Arleigh Burke|destroyer}}s and no longer needed the next-generation DDG-1000 class;<ref>{{cite web |title=Navy DDG-51 and DDG-1000 Destroyer Programs: Background and Issues for Congress |url=https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/RL/RL32109/264 |publisher=Congressional Research Service |access-date=2 October 2022 |page=24 |date=26 August 2022}}</ref><ref name="noneed">{{cite web |url=http://archive.navytimes.com/article/20080731/NEWS/807310319/Navy-No-need-add-DDG-1000s-after-all |title=Navy: No Need to Add DDG 1000s After All |work=Navy Times |publisher=Gannett Government Media |date=31 July 2008 |access-date=25 January 2016}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> only the two approved destroyers would be built. The Navy said the world threat picture had changed in such a way that it made more sense to build at least eight more ''Burke''s rather than DDG-1000s.<ref name="noneed" /> The Navy concluded from fifteen classified intelligence reports that the DDG-1000s would be vulnerable to forms of missile attacks.<ref name="Smith and Nakashima">{{cite news |first1=R. Jeffrey |last1=Smith |first2=Ellen |last2=Nakashima |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/03/07/AR2009030702216.html?hpid=topnews |title=Pentagon's Unwanted Projects in Earmarks |newspaper=The Washington Post|date=8 March 2009 |pages=A01 |access-date=19 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161226111134/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/03/07/AR2009030702216.html?hpid=topnews |archive-date=26 December 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> Many Congressional subcommittee members questioned that the Navy completed such a sweeping re-evaluation of the world threat picture in just a few weeks, after spending some 13 years and $10&nbsp;billion on the development of the surface ship program known as DD-21, then DD(X), and finally DDG-1000.<ref name="noneed" /> Subsequently, Chief of Naval Operations [[Gary Roughead]] cited the need to provide area air defense and specific new threats such as ballistic missiles and the possession of anti-ship missiles by groups such as [[Hezbollah]].<ref name="Roughead">{{cite journal |last=Cavas |first=Christopher P |url=http://www.navytimes.com/news/2008/09/defense_roughead_092408/ |title=Roughead pushes for littoral combat ship |date=26 September 2008 |journal=Navy Times}}</ref> The mooted structural problems have not been discussed in public. [[United States Secretary of the Navy|Navy Secretary]] [[Donald Winter]] said on 4 September, "Making certain that we have—I'll just say, a destroyer—in the '09 budget is more important than whether that's a DDG 1000 or a DDG 51".<ref name="Navytimes080916" />

On 19 August 2008, Secretary Winter said that a third ''Zumwalt'' would be built at Bath Iron Works, citing concerns about maintaining shipbuilding capacity.<ref>{{cite web|first=Philip |last=Ewing |url=http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=3682875 |title=Lawmaker: Third DDG 1000 Far From Done Deal |work=Defense News |date=19 August 2008}}{{dead link|date=August 2021|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> House Defense Appropriations Subcommittee Chairman [[John Murtha]] said on 23 September 2008 that he had agreed to partial funding of the third DDG-1000 in the 2009 Defense authorization bill.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Scully |first=Megan |title=Negotiators agree to buy more F-22s, Zumwalt destroyers |url=http://www.govexec.com/story_page.cfm?articleid=41042 |journal=Congress Daily |date=24 September 2008 |access-date=11 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114120319/http://www.govexec.com/story_page.cfm?articleid=41042 |archive-date=14 January 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

{{Quote box|align=right
|title =Est. combined procurement cost for 3 ships<ref name=cost_april2016/>
|quote=
{{Chart|definition=Zumwalt-class destroyer procurement cost.chart|data=Zumwalt-class destroyer procurement cost.tab|Width=300}}
}}
A 26 January 2009 memo from [[John J. Young Jr.|John Young]], the US [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]]'s (DoD) top acquisition official, stated that the per ship price for the ''Zumwalt''-class destroyers had reached $5.964&nbsp;billion, 81 percent over the Navy's original estimate used in proposing the program, resulting in a breach of the [[Nunn–McCurdy Amendment]], requiring the Navy to re-certify and re-justify the program to Congress or to cancel its production.<ref>{{citation |last=Cavas |first=Christopher P. |title=New Destroyer Emerges in US Plans |work=[[Defense News]] |date=2 February 2009 |pages=1}}</ref>

On 6 April 2009, [[United States Secretary of Defense|Defense Secretary]] [[Robert Gates]] announced that the DoD's proposed 2010 budget would end the DDG-1000 program at a maximum of three ships.<ref name="DefNews proposed 2010 budget">{{cite web |last1=Bennett |first1=John T. |first2=Kris |last2=Osborn |url=http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4026294&c=AME&s=LAN |title=Gates Reveals DoD Program Overhaul |work=Defense News |date=6 April 2009}}{{dead link|date=August 2021|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> In April, [[the Pentagon]] awarded a fixed-price contract with General Dynamics to build the three destroyers, replacing a cost-plus-fee contract that had been awarded to Northrop Grumman. At that time, the first DDG-1000 destroyer was expected to cost $3.5&nbsp;billion, the second approximately $2.5&nbsp;billion, and the third even less.<ref>{{cite news |last=Drew |first=Christopher |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/18/business/18ships.html |title=General Dynamics To Build New Destroyer |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=18 April 2009 |access-date=28 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701094732/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/18/business/18ships.html |archive-date=1 July 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>

What had once been seen as the backbone of the Navy's future surface fleet with a planned production run of 32 has since been replaced by destroyer production reverting to the ''Arleigh Burke'' class after ordering three ''Zumwalt''s.<ref name="ddg background" /> In April 2016, the [[United States Naval Institute|US Naval Institute]] stated that the total cost of the three ''Zumwalt'' ships is about $22.5&nbsp;billion with research and development costs, which is an average of $7.5&nbsp;billion per ship.<ref name=cost_april2016/>

===Construction===
[[File:US Navy 080214-N-0923G-001 Susan Tomaiko, left, and Brian Cuccias, vice president and DDG 1000 program manager for Northrup Grumman Shipbuilding, sign the $1.4 billion construction contract for the DDG 1000 Zumwalt Class destro.jpg|thumb|left|Representatives from Naval Sea Systems Command and Bath Iron Works sign a construction contract at the Pentagon, February 2008.]]

In late 2005, the program entered the detailed design and integration phase, for which [[Raytheon]] was the Mission Systems Integrator. Both Northrop Grumman Ship Systems and General Dynamics Bath Iron Works shared dual-lead for the hull, mechanical, and electrical detailed design. [[BAE Systems Inc.]] had the advanced gun system and the Mk 57 [[Vertical Launching System]] (VLS). Almost every major defense contractor (including [[Lockheed Martin]], Northrop Grumman Sperry Marine, and [[L-3 Communications]]) and subcontractors from nearly every state in the U.S. were involved to some extent in this project, which was the largest single line item in the Navy's budget. During the previous contract, the development and testing of 11 Engineering Development Models (EDMs) took place: Advanced Gun System, Autonomic Fire Suppression System, Dual Band Radar [X-band and L-band], Infrared, Integrated Deckhouse & Apertures, Integrated Power System, Integrated Undersea Warfare, Peripheral Vertical Launch System, Total Ship Computing Environment Infrastructure (TSCEI), [[Tumblehome]] Hull Form. The decision in September 2006 to fund two ships meant that one could be built by the Bath Iron Works in Maine and one by Northrop Grumman's Ingalls Shipbuilding in Mississippi.<ref name="AP060926" />

Northrop Grumman was awarded a $90M contract modification for materials and production planning on 13 November 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irconnect.com/noc/press/pages/news_releases.html?d=131314 |title=U.S. Navy Awards Northrop Grumman $90 Million Long-Lead Material Contract for DDG 1000 |publisher=Northrop Grumman Corporation |date=13 November 2007 |access-date=11 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090102182828/http://www.irconnect.com/noc/press/pages/news_releases.html?d=131314 |archive-date=2 January 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 14 February 2008, Bath Iron Works was awarded a contract for the construction of {{USS|Zumwalt|DDG-1000|3}}, and Northrop Grumman Shipbuilding was awarded a contract for the construction of {{USS|Michael Monsoor|DDG-1001|3}} at a cost of $1.4&nbsp;billion each.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.navy.mil/search/display.asp?story_id=35020 |title=Navy Awards Contracts for Zumwalt Class Destroyers |number=NNS080214-20 |date=14 February 2008 |publisher=Navy News Service |access-date=16 May 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080409005030/http://www.navy.mil/search/display.asp?story_id=35020 |archive-date=9 April 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref>

[[File:The boathouse of USS Zumwalt is moved into position. (8291331134).jpg|thumb|Deckhouse of USS ''Zumwalt'' being installed in December 2012]]
On 11 February 2009, full-rate production officially began on the first ''Zumwalt''-class destroyer.<ref name="BIW News February 2009">{{cite web |url=https://www.gdbiw.com/sites/default/files/docs/BIW%20News/BIWNews_Feb09_web.pdf |title=BIW News February 2009 |date=1 March 2009 |publisher=General Dynamics Bath Iron Works |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414205133/https://www.gdbiw.com/sites/default/files/docs/BIW%20News/BIWNews_Feb09_web.pdf |archive-date=14 April 2012}}</ref> Construction on the second ship of the class, ''Michael Monsoor'', began in March 2010.<ref name="autogeneratedmil">{{cite web |url=http://www.navsea.navy.mil/Newswire2011/17NOV11-01.aspx |title=Keel Laid for First DDG 1000 Destroyer |website= NavSea |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141029223027/http://www.navsea.navy.mil/Newswire2011/17NOV11-01.aspx |archive-date=2014-10-29 |id=NOV17-01}}</ref> The [[keel]] for the first ''Zumwalt''-class destroyer was laid on 17 November 2011.<ref name="autogeneratedmil" /> This first vessel was [[Ship naming and launching|launched]] from the shipyard at Bath, Maine, on 29 October 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://gizmodo.com/americas-21st-century-destroyer-set-sail-for-the-first-1443932986/1454286967/@andrewtarantola |last=Tarantola |first=Andrew |title=America's Newest and Deadliest Destroyer Has Finally Set Sail |publisher=Gizmodo.com |date=29 October 2013 |access-date=12 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140326114441/http://gizmodo.com/americas-21st-century-destroyer-set-sail-for-the-first-1443932986/1454286967/@andrewtarantola |archive-date=26 March 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>

The construction timetable in July 2008 was:<ref name="GAO-08-804">{{cite web |url=http://www.gao.gov/products/GAO-08-804 |title=GAO-08-804, Defense Acquisitions: Cost to Deliver Zumwalt-Class Destroyers Likely to Exceed Budget |date=31 July 2008 |publisher=Government Accountability Office |access-date=29 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013145032/http://www.gao.gov/products/GAO-08-804 |archive-date=13 October 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref><!-- has some useful history of program-->
* October 2008: DDG-1000 starts construction at Bath Iron Works
* September 2009: DDG-1001 starts construction at Bath Iron Works.
* April 2012: DDG-1002 starts construction at Bath Iron Works
* April 2013: DDG-1000 initial delivery
* May 2014: DDG-1001 initial delivery
* March 2015: DDG-1001 Initial operating capability
* December 2018: DDG-1002 initial delivery

The Navy planned for ''Zumwalt'' to reach initial operating capability (IOC) in 2016. The second ship, ''Michael Monsoor'', was commissioned in 2019, and the third ship, {{USS|Lyndon B. Johnson|DDG-1002|3}}, was to have reached IOC in 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dodbuzz.com/2014/01/14/ddg-1000-preps-for-heavy-weather-trials/ |title=DDG 1000 Preps for Heavy Weather Trials |last=Osborn |first=Kris |website=DoDBuzz.com |date=14 January 2014 |access-date=15 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116091714/http://www.dodbuzz.com/2014/01/14/ddg-1000-preps-for-heavy-weather-trials/ |archive-date=16 January 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>

== Ships in class ==
In April 2006, the Navy announced plans to name the first ship of the class ''Zumwalt'' after former Chief of Naval Operations Admiral [[Elmo Zumwalt|Elmo R. "Bud" Zumwalt Jr.]]<ref name="GAO-08-804" /> The vessel's hull number would be DDG-1000, which abandoned the guided-missile destroyer sequence used by the ''Arleigh Burke'' class destroyers (DDG-51–) and continued the previous "gun destroyer" sequence from the last of the {{sclass|Spruance|destroyer|4}}, {{USS|Hayler|DD-997|3}}.{{Dubious|date=May 2026|reason=If the Zumwalt had continued where the original destroyer sequence left off, then it would have been numbered "DDG-998" rather than "DDG-1000"}}

The Navy announced on 29 October 2008 that DDG-1001 would be named for Master-at-Arms 2nd Class [[Michael A. Monsoor]], the second [[United States Navy SEAL|Navy SEAL]] to receive the [[Medal of Honor]] during the [[Battle of Ramadi (2006)]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://hamptonroads.com/node/486137 |title=Navy to name newest destroyer after SEAL who died in Iraq |first=Cindy |last=Clayton |work=[[The Virginian-Pilot]] |date=30 October 2008 |access-date=22 April 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522121457/http://hamptonroads.com/node/486137 |archive-date=22 May 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> in the [[Iraq War]]. Monsoor had deliberately [[Falling on a grenade|fallen upon a grenade]] to reduce danger to his SEAL teammates.

On 16 April 2012, [[Secretary of the Navy]] [[Ray Mabus]] announced that DDG-1002 would be named for former naval officer and U.S. President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defense.gov/releases/release.aspx?releaseid=15190 |title=Navy Names Zumwalt Class Destroyer USS Lyndon B. Johnson |publisher=Office of the Assistant Secretary of Defense (Public Affairs), [[United States Department of Defense]] |date=16 April 2012 |access-date=2012-04-16 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120515081343/http://www.defense.gov/releases/release.aspx?releaseid=15190 |archive-date=15 May 2012}}</ref>

The Navy chose to use an unusual two-part [[Ship commissioning|commissioning]] scheme for the ships. The initial commissioning was done prior to weapons systems integration, and the ships were placed in the status of "in commission, special" before sailing to San Diego for weapons installation and final acceptance. The first two ships used this approach, while the last one will use the more traditional approach with formal commissioning after final acceptance.<ref name="special commissioning">{{cite web
 |url=https://seapowermagazine.org/geurts-third-zumwalt-ddg-will-be-commissioned-after-combat-systems-activation/
 |title=Geurts: Third Zumwalt DDG Will Be Commissioned After Combat Systems Activation
